Repeated sampling

sim_mean_sd = function(n_obs, mu = 5, sigma = 1){
  x_vec = rnorm(n = n_obs, mean = mu, sd = sigma)
  tibble(
  mean = mean(x_vec),
  sd = sd(x_vec)
)
}

output = vector("list", length = 100)
for (i in 1:100) {
  output[[i]] = sim_mean_sd(n_obs = 30)
}

sim_results = bind_rows(output)
sim_results |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = mean))+
  geom_density()

sim_results |> 
  summarise(mu_hat = mean(mean),
            sd_hat = sd(mean))
## # A tibble: 1  2
##   mu_hat sd_hat
##    <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1   5.00  0.193

use a map function

sim_results_df = 
  expand_grid(
    sample_size = c(30, 60, 120, 240),
    iter = 1:1000
  ) |> 
  mutate(estimate_df = map(sample_size, sim_mean_sd)) |> 
  unnest(estimate_df)

sim_results_df |> 
  mutate(
    sample_size = str_c("n = ", sample_size),
    sample_size = fct_inorder(sample_size)
  ) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = sample_size, y = mean)) +
  geom_boxplot()

Simulation regression: goal is to write a function that simulates data and then fits a regression, then repeat to look at the distribution of estimated coefficients

sim_regression = function(n, beta0 = 2, beta1 = 3) {
  
  sim_data = 
    tibble(
      x = rnorm(n, mean = 1, sd = 1),
      y = beta0 + beta1 * x + rnorm(n, 0, 1)
    )
  
  ls_fit = lm(y ~ x, data = sim_data)
  
  tibble(
    beta0_hat = coef(ls_fit)[1],
    beta1_hat = coef(ls_fit)[2]
  )
}

sim_results_df = 
  expand_grid(
    sample_size = 30,
    iter = 1:500
  ) |> 
  mutate(
    estimate_df = map(sample_size, sim_regression)
  ) |> 
  unnest(estimate_df)

sim_results_df |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = beta0_hat))+
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

sim_results_df |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = beta0_hat, y = beta1_hat)) + 
  geom_point()
